defaultSubmission from the Centre for CitiesdefaultExecutive Summarydefault1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBritons work, live and socialise across, and regardless of, administrative boundaries. Nearly 50 per cent of commuters 
defaultto
default cities live and work in different local authorities.
default But neither central government nor local authorities govern or manage budgets at this scale. 
default1.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe challenge for UK cities is this: how can one local authority afford to invest in growth if the financial (as well as social and environmental) benefits accrue to Whitehall or neighbouring authorities? The costs of unlocking growth often fall on one loc
defaultal authority, while the benefits are widespread. This means the finances for development projects often do not stack up. Cities 
defaultand city regions 
defaultneed greater control over how they spend money, 
defaultfreedom to raise funding of their own and governance structures
default that reflect the economy and enable services to be delivered 
defaultmore efficiently and effectively 
defaultat scale.
default1.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevolution will not 
defaultinevitably
default lead to increased economic growth but we do know that the current 
defaultcentralised 
defaultsystem 
defaultrestricts growth opportunities
default: str
defaultuggling areas are maintained but areas that could grow more are held back. By providing freedoms, tools and incentives to local authorities, devolution would enable cities to unlock their full potential. 
default1.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBut devolution in itself
default is not a silver bullet for
default growth everywhere. Not all places have the same opportunities and variation will inevitably increase as places that have more to gain from devolution grow their economies. 
defaultAreas with structural barriers to growth should be helped in different ways to fast
default-growing areas, particularly through minimum standards of redistribution and targeted support. And devolution should
default enable cities to generate additional funds, some of which can be redistributed. 
default1.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe focus for
default 
defaultCentre for Cities 
defaultis to improve the economie
defaults of UK cities and the surrounding areas that support urban economies, because evidence shows these are the most effective places to improve the national economy as 
defaulta 
defaultwhole. 
defaultO
defaultur submission focus
defaultes
default primarily on the existing challenges to growth in cities, o
defaultr functional economic areas, and why devolution is the answer
default – a
defaultlthough we also note that there are some freedoms and flexibilities, such as business rates, which should be devolved to all local authorities, urban and rural
default. Ultimately, a process of 
defaulttailo
defaultred 
defaultdevolution provides the best solution
default, with cities and city regions being a priority for greater freedoms and flexibilities
default. With the freedoms and incentives necessary to invest in the services needed – and to do so at scale, in collaboration – cities 
defaultand city regions 
defaultcan improve their economies but also those of neighbouring areas that depend on them
default, whether urban, suburban or rural
default. 
default2.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCity governments are investors: in the local economy, in society and in their residents and businesses.  But they do not have the powers and resources to effectively manage their assets: the balance of powers and financial control still lies within Whiteha
defaultll. And while the onus is on local government to deliver local services and support economic growth, it has minimal control over how it manages its finances to invest in growth. Government needs to pass responsibility on to cities – functional economies co
defaultvering multiple local 
defaultauthorities – enabling them to capitalise on local knowledge, incentivise cross-boundary strategies and leverage capital and services investments off one another. 
default2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe figure below shows the spectrum of control Government has over loc
defaultal government income streams, demonstrating that cities and city regions need more financial powers to deliver growth. 
